4 I wasn't sure what to expect when we arrived at Flemings, but I knew it would be pretty nice. Their dining area is set up in a big open space so the noise level can be pretty loud. Lighting is intimate, decor is nice and for a Saturday night we couldn't get reservations till 8:45 pm.  Since it was so late and we were starving, we started off with the Baked Brie. It was toasty flakey goodness with lots of melty cheese. My husband totally loved it, I liked it, but I loved the apples more. It was fairly rich though so we could not finish it all. I ended up ordering the Petit Filet Mignon (8 oz) and the husband ordered the ribeye. We ordered the Fleming's potatoes and creamed spinach for sides. My petit was cooked perfectly and I really could only eat about half of it before I gave it to my husband. I didn't try his ribeye but from what I could tell by his empty plate he loved it. Fleming's potatoes were the highlight of my life....me and potatoes are besties! I wonder if I could order this again to go....even though it had jalapenos in it, it had no heat. I could have used a lil bit of heat which is surprising since I am such a wuss when it comes to spicy foods. We were too full for dessert so we opted out. (Forgot to mention that I love the Bernaise sauce and the husband enjoyed the Madiera sauce I think!  Service was alright.....I wasn't too impressed as the server had dropped off our check and we waited about 15 minutes before we gave our card to someone else to take care of. The server was chatting with friends and being as we were one of the last ones there, you would think service would be better. That kind of ruined my experience, but I got over it and I definitely want to try Flemings for their happy hour.    P.S. Their complimentary cheese bread and sun dried tomato buttah is heaven!
